                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d233">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A5/121: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-06-29T17:00:00+03:00"
                            >June 29, 1934—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 30—4:27 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>162. Your 141, June 27, 7 p.m. Mr. Frederic Kuh recently visited Moscow and was
                    received twice by me and Mr. Wiley.<note n="13" xml:id="d233fn13">John C. Wiley,
                        Counselor of Embassy.</note> Neither of us discussed with him any matter
                    touching in any way on the preliminary naval conversations or on American
                    policy. It is well known that Kuh for years has been in intimate contact with
                    the Soviet Foreign Office and I suspect that the activities in London attributed
                    to him have been at the behest of Litvinov<note n="14" xml:id="d233fn14">Maxim
                        Litvinov, Soviet Commissar for Foreign Affairs.</note> whom he saw on the
                    eve of his departure.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
